bryos <br>• Gametes <br>• Ovarian/Testicular tissue | **Source files:** <br>• Content (e.g., Markdown files) <br>• Templates (e.g., HTML, Liquid, Nunjucks) <br>• Data files (e.g., JSON, YAML) |\n| **The End Product** | A **physical inventory** of cryopreserved samples stored in liquid nitrogen. | A **folder of static files** (HTML, CSS, JavaScript) ready to be deployed to a web server. This is the \"website.\" |\n| **Role of \"Structured Data\"** | The \"data\" is the **intrinsic genetic code (DNA)** within the cells. It is implicit, biological, and not easily separated from the physical sample. | The data is **explicit metadata** kept in separate files (e.g., a `doctors.json` file) or in the \"front matter\" of a content file. This data is used by the generator to populate templates. |\n| **Tools Used** | **Laboratory Equipment:** <br>• Cryotanks, vitrification tools, microscopes. | **Software Tools:** <br>• SSGs (Hugo, Jekyll, Eleventy, Next.js) <br>• Code editors, command line, version control (Git). |\n\n---\n\n### How Could They Connect?\n\nThis is where your question gets really interesting. While the processes themselves are worlds apart, a **Static-Site Generator using structured data is the perfect technology to build a website *for* an organization that performs EGGF.**\n\nImagine a leading fertility research institute. They need a website that is fast, secure (to build trust), and easy to update with the latest research and staff information. They decide to use an SSG.\n\nHere’s how they would use it:\n\n1.  **Content in Markdown:** Their informational pages (\"About Us,\" \"Our Mission,\" \"FAQ\") are written as simple Markdown files.\n2.  **Structured Data for Key Info:** Instead of hard-coding information into HTML pages, they store it in structured data files in a `_data` folder:\n    *   `procedures.yaml`: A file listing all the services they offer, including a detailed entry for \"EGGF,\" its description, success rates, and cost.\n    *   `doctors.json`: A list of all their specialists with their names, credentials, photos, and biographies.\n    *   `publications.yaml`: A list of all research papers published by their team.\n3.  **The SSG Builds the Site:** When they run the SSG, it:\n    *   Reads the `procedures.yaml` file and creates a beautiful, detailed web page for each service.\n    *   Reads the `doctors.json` file and generates a staff directory and individual profile pages for each doctor.\n    *   Inserts the correct doctor's information at the bottom of the research papers they authored.\n4.  **Embedded Structured Data (schema.org):** For SEO purposes, their website templates are designed to embed `schema.org` structured data (in JSON-LD format) into the final HTML. This tells Google:\n    *   \"This page is about a `MedicalProcedure` called EGGF.\"\n    *   \"This page is about a `Physician` named Dr. Smith.\"\n    *   \"This is the website for a `MedicalClinic`.\"\n\nIn this scenario:\n*   The **EGGF** is the high-tech, real-world medical service the institute provides.\n*   The **SSG with Structured Data** is the high-tech, digital tool they use to create a public-facing website that accurately and efficiently describes that service.\n\n### Summary\n\n| | **EGGF** | **Static-Site Generator** |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Realm** | Physical / Biological | Digital / Informational |\n| **What it produces** | The potential for a new life | A website |\n| **Analogy** | **The vintage wine** in the bottle | **The machine that prints the wine labels** from a template and a spreadsheet |",
